I'm a big fan of Abe Maslow.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:36.279
I took one, a grand total of one psychology
class as Stanford.

00:09:36.279 --> 00:09:41.110
I went to Stanford undergrad, I went to Stanford
Business School, I took a class with Zimbardo,

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:42.860
Phil Zimbardo, Phillip Zimbardo.

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:47.730
So he was my psychology professor and the
one thing I remember from psychology one,

00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:52.360
in college was Abe Maslow because he was the
guy who talked about best practices in human

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:54.610
behavior as opposed to worst practices.

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:59.819
He's also the one who came up a great quote,
"If the only tool you have is a hammer, everything

00:09:59.819 --> 00:10:01.589
starts to look like a nail."

00:10:01.589 --> 00:10:04.589
And he said that to the psychology profession,
he said, "Why is it that we think that all

00:10:04.589 --> 00:10:05.589
people are broken?

00:10:05.589 --> 00:10:08.250
Why don't we study the flourishing people?

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:12.410
And by studying the people who are flourishing
or self actualizing in life maybe we can learn

00:10:12.410 --> 00:10:14.699
something that we can apply to everybody else."

00:10:14.699 --> 00:10:17.860
And that's why he created the hierarchy of
needs.

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:24.310
