00:11:10.339 --> 00:11:12.769
and two goys named Chip.

00:11:12.769 --> 00:11:18.769
And the last downturn, I felt a bit like a
gladiator and my company Joie de Vivre lived

00:11:18.769 --> 00:11:24.410
up to its name, Joy of Life, and we used Maslow
to get ourselves through it.

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:29.220
This downturn, I wasn't feeling so much that
way, I actually was feeling quite the opposite.

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:34.829
I felt more like a prisoner than a gladiator.

00:11:34.829 --> 00:11:40.209
And so I started reading this book by Viktor
Frankl called Man's Search for Meaning.

00:11:40.209 --> 00:11:42.069
How many of you are familiar with the book?

00:11:42.069 --> 00:11:44.480
So a handful of you folks.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:48.180
So Man's Search for Meaning was written by
Viktor Frankl in the 1940's.

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:55.699
He was a Jewish psychologist in Vienna in
the 1930's and his basic premise as a psychologist

00:11:55.699 --> 00:12:03.759
was that the fuel of life is meaning; that's
what creates the sense of why we show up for

00:12:03.759 --> 00:12:05.399
our lives each day.

00:12:05.399 --> 00:12:11.769
And then, ironically, and sort of as if God
as a weird sense of humor, he was put in a

00:12:11.769 --> 00:12:18.170
concentration camp to see if his theory of
meaning being the fuel of life actually made

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:19.170
sense.

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:24.190
He ended up writing about it and I started
reading this book in early 2008.

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:29.160
Peak, my book came out in September of 2007
and I was goin' around the country and giving

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:35.540
about 80 speeches a year on self-actualization
in the context of work, including here at

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:36.910
Google.

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:41.129
But in early 2008 I was very clear that my
life wasn't, I was like the guy going out

00:12:41.129 --> 00:12:43.410
and talking about self actualization but not
feeling it --

00:12:43.410 --> 00:12:44.410
[laughter]

00:12:44.410 --> 00:12:47.490
which was a really awkward, it's like the
preacher going out and giving his sermon and

00:12:47.490 --> 00:12:51.220
then going out and doin' something that we
won't talk about here, you know what those

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:52.660
preachers do.

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:53.660
[laughter]

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:58.380
And I ended up starting to read this book
because I felt like I was a bit of a prisoner

00:12:58.380 --> 00:13:03.509
to my identity and to what was the upcoming
downturn that I could sort of see.

00:13:03.509 --> 00:13:06.649
'Cause the hotel industry basically can see
downturns.

00:13:06.649 --> 00:13:10.050
You see downturns faster than we do because
of the analytics associated with what goes

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:11.050
on with Google.

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:14.209
We see it pretty quickly though, too, because
one of the first things people cut back on

00:13:14.209 --> 00:13:15.890
in terms of spending is travel.

00:13:15.890 --> 00:13:21.519
But there was a quote in Man's Search for
Meaning that really spoke to me on a deep

00:13:21.519 --> 00:13:26.920
level and it was this one: "Between stimulus
and response there is a space.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:34.199
In that space is our power to choose our response
and in our response lies our growth and our

00:13:34.199 --> 00:13:35.199
freedom."

00:13:35.199 --> 00:13:40.990
So for me, I mean like who's the whining CEO,
Chip Conley, up there like being upset about

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:41.990
his life.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:43.620
Well, I wasn't whining about it.

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:48.410
In fact, I had this growing divide between
my public image and my private reality and

00:13:48.410 --> 00:13:52.139
when that happens that's actually quite often
when depression and a few other things can

00:13:52.139 --> 00:13:53.139
kick in.

00:13:53.139 --> 00:13:58.660
Well, I had other friends in my life who had
a growing divide between their public image

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:01.499
and their private reality too.

