And I just went unconscious and within about
five minutes the paramedics were there and

00:16:15.649 --> 00:16:19.110
they put heart monitors on me and that's when
I went flat line.

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:23.360
So between that and a bunch of other things
happening in my life, a long term relationship

00:16:23.360 --> 00:16:28.589
ending, my son going to San Quentin wrongfully,
he ended up getting out after being eight

00:16:28.589 --> 00:16:29.589
months in San Quentin.

00:16:29.589 --> 00:16:34.040
A federal judge let him out but [chuckles]
having your son go to San Quentin for eight

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:36.040
months is not a fun thing.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:39.800
And then we were running out of money, as
a company, and I was running out of money,

00:16:39.800 --> 00:16:40.800
personally.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:47.759
So I took Man's Search for Meaning and I said,
"You know, what I want this, I wanna understand

00:16:47.759 --> 00:16:54.779
why I wanna continue to stand and be on this
earth and I don't wanna go the path that Chip

00:16:54.779 --> 00:16:58.190
and others felt like they had to take."

00:16:58.190 --> 00:17:05.079
So I turned this famous book on meaning into
an equation and I am not a math major, I am

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:11.209
so far from a math [chuckles] major, but what
I needed was something to help to explain

00:17:11.209 --> 00:17:16.390
the relationship between the components that
were creating some depression and despair

00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:18.360
in my life.

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:22.330
So this was the equation: Despair equals suffering
minus meaning.

00:17:22.330 --> 00:17:24.710
It's a little bit like sacred algebra.

00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:26.080
[chuckles]

00:17:26.080 --> 00:17:30.490
Suffering was the constant, if you're going
through a really rough time in your life suffering

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:36.840
is a constant; if you're a Buddhist its first
noble truth of Buddhism that suffering, Dukkha,

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:39.740
is ever present.

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:43.820
Having Meng in the front row is really hard,
it's very distracting right now.

00:17:43.820 --> 00:17:45.420
[laughs]

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:47.030
[laughter]

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:48.640
[pause]

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:50.270
Between Meng and between the Ph.

00:17:50.270 --> 00:17:55.080
D. math people in the room, it's like okay
I am really setting myself up for failure

00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:56.080
today.

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:57.080
[laughter]

00:17:57.080 --> 00:18:03.400
No, but suffering is ever present when you're
going through a really rough time and the

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:08.510
funny thing about it, the sad thing about
it is we tend to actually focus on it and

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:11.620
when you're focusing on it you're not making
it any better.

00:18:11.620 --> 00:18:15.630
What this helped me to see is that suffering
is the constant and meaning's the variable

00:18:15.630 --> 00:18:19.640
and if you put your attention on the meaning
and increase the meaning, the despair goes

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:21.120
down.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:26.560
And that was my own little mantra that I was
using in the summer of 2008 after my flat

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:30.320
line experience when I was goin' through a
bunch of other crap.

00:18:30.320 --> 00:18:33.830
And it was working for me because what it
helped me to get back to is, like, what's

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:37.940
the lesson, with all this stuff that's goin'
on, what's the lesson?

00:18:37.940 --> 00:18:44.790
I also found a study, a really interesting
study, of women who grew up during the Civil

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:48.510
War, I'm sorry, during the Depression.

00:18:48.510 --> 00:18:51.150
Women who grew up in the 1930s.

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:55.150
And what it showed was that women who actually
grew up in the 1930s in their formative years

00:18:55.150 --> 00:19:00.221
later in life when they became a widow because
quite often they outlive their husband, they

00:19:00.221 --> 00:19:07.520
actually had built, during the 1930s in their
teens and their 20s, resilience, independence,

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:08.520
courage.

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:13.450
They were better able to handle being a widow
than the women who didn't grow up during the

00:19:13.450 --> 00:19:14.450
Depression.

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:19.660
Major study by Elker and Lighter that was
done like 10, 20 years ago.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:22.590
So I said, "Okay maybe I'm actually in emotional
boot camp right now.

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:26.370
And maybe during emotional boot camp, I'm
actually building some emotional muscles that

00:19:26.370 --> 00:19:30.480
I have but I hadn't been working out in a
while."

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:33.450
And so that's what I started to think about.

00:19:33.450 --> 00:19:39.090
And then in November of 2008, when the world
was starting to fall apart in a faster pace,

00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:41.560
it was two months after Lehman Brothers went
bankrupt.

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:46.990
And in the hotel business, people in our company
could say, "My God, we're about to go into

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:51.510
our second once-in-a-lifetime downturn in
the same decade."

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:55.910
I was supposed to give a speech to the top
18, I'm sorry the top 80 executives in my

00:19:55.910 --> 00:19:59.450
company at the Dream Inn in Santa Cruz which
is, if you haven't been there lately, it's

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:01.760
a hotel we renovated a couple years ago.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:03.590
It's sort of cool.

00:20:03.590 --> 00:20:07.300
And we were all sitting looking at the view
and everybody was looking for the cheerleading

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:10.020
speech from Chip the CEO.

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:13.730
And instead of giving the cheerleading speech,
I threw it away because what I saw in the

00:20:13.730 --> 00:20:17.580
room was 80 people who were full of suffering.

00:20:17.580 --> 00:20:22.860
And so I just said, on an easel, I just wrote
up my equation and I said, "I wanna just share

00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:26.710
for the next hour my equation with you because
I actually think the worse thing I could do

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:29.760
right now is to be up here cheerleading.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:33.830
And I, instead, think we need to do what Abe
Maslow talked about is we need to have a good

00:20:33.830 --> 00:20:35.930
exercise in psycho hygiene.

00:20:35.930 --> 00:20:36.930
[chuckles]

00:20:36.930 --> 00:20:42.340
Psycho hygiene basically, means in Maslow
term, it means that when you're going through

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:46.370
a really difficult time, you learn how to
shower together.

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:51.630
[chuckles] Because frankly what happens in
an organization during difficult times is

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:56.580
there's a lot of stress, it becomes a bit
of a sweat box, and actually people sort of

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:59.960
go at each other instead of actually sort
of figuring out how to actually make people

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:01.700
feel a little bit better.

00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:06.480
So I felt like what we needed to do is actually
be authentic and vulnerable and allow people

00:21:06.480 --> 00:21:11.410
to talk about their fears about being a general
manager of a hotel that has just two years

00:21:11.410 --> 00:21:15.320
ago got through the last downturn and now
we're going into another one.

00:21:15.320 --> 00:21:21.060
So an hour later after the talk and people
conversing and people telling their stories

00:21:21.060 --> 00:21:26.040
someone came up to me and gave me a whisper
and said, "Do you have an equation for jealousy?"

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:27.040
[laughs]

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:28.040
[laughter]

00:21:28.040 --> 00:21:31.540
And someone else came up and said, "Do you
have one for anxiety?"

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:36.560
And then the smartest one in the room came
up and said, "Do you have one for happiness?"

00:21:36.560 --> 00:21:40.370
So I said, "This is interesting."

00:21:40.370 --> 00:21:44.530
I created this equation for myself and then
I shared it with my senior executives and

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:51.060
it seemed to actually resonate so I said,
"I wanna learn more about emotions."

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:56.160
This is Isaac Newton, really smart dude [laughs]
I mean come on now you know that he actually

00:21:56.160 --> 00:22:02.450
helped to invent calculus, I don't know if
you can invent calculus, but he was able to

00:22:02.450 --> 00:22:07.170
sort of help us understand calculus; gravity,
he didn't invent it but he helped us explain

00:22:07.170 --> 00:22:09.270
it; the telescope.

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:13.140
But you probably didn't know that Isaac Newton
also created the color wheel and helped us

00:22:13.140 --> 00:22:19.150
to understand that if you combine red plus
blue you get purple.

00:22:19.150 --> 00:22:21.310
So I didn't know that Isaac Newton did that.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:26.370
Well as I started to look at the color wheel
I started to see well this idea of despair

00:22:26.370 --> 00:22:30.510
equals suffering minus meaning is sort of,
it's like an emotion wheel.

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:33.570
And I did my deep dive, I did sort of my Ph.

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:38.820
D. in psychology and I spent the next year
and a half to two years learning and reading

00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:42.270
about 150 books and 300 studies in psychology.

00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:46.760
And I learned about this guy Dr. Robert Plutchik
who had created in the 1980's something called

00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:47.760
the emotion wheel.

00:22:47.760 --> 00:22:52.270
You can't really see it very well up here
but if you add joy plus anticipation it equals

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:53.270
optimism.

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:57.710
And he created this emotion wheel and the
reason that it never got a lot of play within

00:22:57.710 --> 00:23:03.820
the psychology academic community, is because
back in the 1980s, if you were doing backwater

00:23:03.820 --> 00:23:09.010
academic studies in psychology you were focusing
on emotions because emotions was not a very

00:23:09.010 --> 00:23:14.850
well respected piece of the psychology world;
today it is, but back then it wasn't.

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:17.140
So it never really got very far.

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:24.160
But I said to myself, "Wow, I guess there's
some history of the psychology academic world

00:23:24.160 --> 00:23:27.910
looking at the idea of equations for emotions.

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:32.100
In fact, I started to learn a little bit more
about the happiness equation that Martin Seligman,

00:23:32.100 --> 00:23:37.290
Marty Seligman, famous positive psychologist
had created where he said, "Happiness is 50

00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:44.850
percent your biological set point, 10 percent
your circumstances, and 40 percent your intention."

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:49.770
So I decided to do a little bit more research
and I decided to go out and study happiness.

00:23:49.770 --> 00:23:51.500
Now I could have gone to Disneyland [chuckles]

00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:52.500
[laughter]

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:56.210
the happiest place on earth which is where
I grew up, I grew up like within five minutes

00:23:56.210 --> 00:23:57.210
of Disneyland --

00:23:57.210 --> 00:23:59.100
[pause]

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:00.560
instead I went to Bhutan.

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:01.580
Why?

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:03.011
Anybody know why Bhutan and happiness?

00:24:03.011 --> 00:24:04.011
Yes.

00:24:04.011 --> 00:24:05.011
&gt;&gt;male #2: Gross national happiness index.

00:24:05.011 --> 00:24:07.480
&gt;&gt;Chip Conley: Yeah, the gross national happiness
index.

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:15.590
So 40 years ago, the 17 year old King of Bhutan
was in India and someone said to him, "What's

00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:21.360
the GDP or actually the GNP because GDP hadn't
been created yet, what's the GNP for Bhutan?"

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:27.380
And the 17 year old king looked at the Indian
journalist and said, "Why do we care about

00:24:27.380 --> 00:24:30.700
GNP, why don't we care about gross national
happiness?"

00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:36.440
Now, at the time, it didn't take a lot of
note, people didn't take much note of it but

00:24:36.440 --> 00:24:40.890
40 years later there are now 50 countries
in the world that are studying their gross

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:44.280
national happiness in some form with some
name.

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:50.050
Bhutan was the first one and because it's
sort of a really cool place, that's Bhutan,

00:24:50.050 --> 00:24:51.920
that's Tiger's Nest in Bhutan.

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:56.250
I said, "I'm gonna go to Bhutan and I'm gonna
spend a week studying the gross national happiness

00:24:56.250 --> 00:25:00.060
index there, get to know the Prime Minister,
get to know the people in the U.N. who are

00:25:00.060 --> 00:25:05.680
there in Bhutan studying happiness and I'll
come back and then I'll go talk to a bunch

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:07.470
of other people on the happiness circuit."

00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:08.470
[laughs]

00:25:08.470 --> 00:25:09.470
[laughter]

00:25:09.470 --> 00:25:15.330
So I did and I came back with this equation
and I was fortunate enough that a guy named

00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:20.870
Chris Anderson, not Chris Anderson, the Wired
Chris Anderson, but Chris Anderson, the TED

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:26.411
Chris Anderson found out about my equation
and asked me to give a finale TED talk two

00:25:26.411 --> 00:25:31.520
years ago at the TED conference and introduced
my happiness equation.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:37.720
So this is a little bit of a mind tease, happiness
equals wanting what you have divided by having

00:25:37.720 --> 00:25:38.720
what you want.

00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:44.230
It comes back to a guy named Rabbi Hyman Schachtel
in 1954 said, "Happiness is not about having

00:25:44.230 --> 00:25:47.970
what you want it's about wanting what you
have."

00:25:47.970 --> 00:25:54.970
And it's learning to actually get to the practicing
of gratitude.

00:25:54.970 --> 00:26:00.070
The psychology profession and those who actually
study happiness basically they all say, "The

00:26:00.070 --> 00:26:04.900
fastest way to create happiness in the moment
when you're not feeling happy is to figure

00:26:04.900 --> 00:26:07.440
out how to get to gratitude as quickly as
possible.

00:26:07.440 --> 00:26:11.130
And it's not just the process of actually
getting to gratitude, it's also the practice

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:13.570
of expressing the gratitude.

00:26:13.570 --> 00:26:18.720
Because actually just experiencing the gratitude
without expressing it is like wrapping a Christmas

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:20.540
present and not giving it.

00:26:20.540 --> 00:26:21.540
[laughs]

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:22.540
[laughter]

00:26:22.540 --> 00:26:27.980
So the idea of practicing gratitude is what
wanting what you have means.

00:26:27.980 --> 00:26:31.850
So when you want what you have, you have a
tendency to practice gratitude, to feel and

00:26:31.850 --> 00:26:33.660
appreciate what you have.

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:39.980
We, in the United States, get very wrapped
up in the denominator of this equation, the

00:26:39.980 --> 00:26:46.150
pursuit of gratification; having what we want;
the act of going out and having what we want.

00:26:46.150 --> 00:26:50.770
Let me tell you, I am a Type A person, I was
a CEO for 24 years, I went to Stanford, I

00:26:50.770 --> 00:26:54.530
went to Stanford Business School, I am a pursuer
by nature.

00:26:54.530 --> 00:26:58.790
So I'm not here to say that we should not
pursue happiness, it's actually in the Declaration

00:26:58.790 --> 00:27:00.910
of Independence of our country.

00:27:00.910 --> 00:27:07.850
But if you look at the dictionary definition
of pursuit in some dictionaries, the definition

00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:11.350
of pursuit is to chase with hostility.

00:27:11.350 --> 00:27:12.350
[laughs]

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:13.350
[laughter]

00:27:13.350 --> 00:27:15.000
Do we chase happiness with hostility --

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.000
[laughter]

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:17.000
in the United States?

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.480
I think on occasion we do.

00:27:18.480 --> 00:27:19.480
[laughter]

00:27:19.480 --> 00:27:27.480
So in some ways, happiness is about how do
you practice gratitude and how to you be careful

00:27:27.480 --> 00:27:30.200
about the pursuing of gratification?

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:34.720
For me, it's not about actually being a couch
potato and just writing in my gratitude journal

00:27:34.720 --> 00:27:37.530
every day, I wouldn't be able to do that very
well.

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:43.990
But it is when I'm in that state of not feeling
very happy about something I can ask myself

00:27:43.990 --> 00:27:47.670
this equation and the question, "How do I
get to gratitude right now?

00:27:47.670 --> 00:27:49.240
How do I practice some gratitude?

00:27:49.240 --> 00:27:53.440
And am I spending too much time in the denominator
in pursuing gratification?"

00:27:53.440 --> 00:27:58.690
The book, this book Emotional Equations which
Books, Inc. is here so they've got, they've

00:27:58.690 --> 00:28:05.020
got discount books, it's lovely that you,
Google, I think, subsidizes them right?

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:09.440
Well this book actually the first week it
was out it went on to the New York Times Best

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:10.640
Sellers List at number seven.

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:15.500
Of course I was, my immediate reaction was
I want number four next week.

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:17.590
[laughs] Because I was pursuing gratification
–

00:28:17.590 --> 00:28:19.110
[pause]

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:22.530
and I saw it immediately and when I could
actually laugh at myself and say, "Damn, I

00:28:22.530 --> 00:28:26.460
wrote a book about emotional equations and
actually did really well and my first reaction

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:29.150
when it did really well was, "I wanna be number
four."

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:30.150
[pause]

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:34.120
So that's how our mind works and it's been
working that way for a long time.

00:28:34.120 --> 00:28:35.610
We know who this guy is.

00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:39.740
What you didn't know about Socrates is he
was the first guy to ever go on a treadmill

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:41.350
and he was the first guy to buy Nikes.

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:42.350
[chuckles]

00:28:42.350 --> 00:28:43.350
[laughter]

00:28:43.350 --> 00:28:51.570
But Socrates once said, "He who is not contented
with what he has would not be contented with

00:28:51.570 --> 00:28:54.640
what he would like to have."

00:28:54.640 --> 00:29:00.160
So on a treadmill because most of you have
probably heard of the hedonic treadmill and

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:04.170
it's a treadmill that we all jump on and it's
the treadmill of gratification.

00:29:04.170 --> 00:29:08.120
How do we go out and pursue our gratification,
how do we go out and get what we want, how

00:29:08.120 --> 00:29:11.510
do we go out and if we've gotten this how
do we go out and get that?

00:29:11.510 --> 00:29:14.700
And generally speaking for those of us who
are leaders we want people working for us

00:29:14.700 --> 00:29:16.000
who have that mentality.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:20.150
So I'm not saying we shouldn't actually have
the pursuit, what I am saying is when you're

00:29:20.150 --> 00:29:25.580
not feeling happy, just know that this is
what's going on and it's been goin' on for

00:29:25.580 --> 00:29:29.330
centuries, going back to Socrates' time.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:34.180
So after getting despair and happiness [chuckles]
I'd gotten the two equations at the extremes

00:29:34.180 --> 00:29:40.900
I started asking myself, "What's the number
one emotion that seems to be pervading organizational

00:29:40.900 --> 00:29:43.270
culture in the United States in this recession?"

00:29:43.270 --> 00:29:46.120
This is 2009 at this point.

00:29:46.120 --> 00:29:47.120
[pause]

00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:52.280
And this is it, it was anxiety, the number
one emotion in most organizations in the world,

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:54.680
especially in a recession.

00:29:54.680 --> 00:30:00.980
There are two ingredients that represent,
according to anxiety researchers, 95 to 96

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:06.310
percent of the anxiety that we tend to feel:
it's what you don't know and what you can't

00:30:06.310 --> 00:30:10.720
control; those are the two variables.

00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:15.720
And so it's anxiety equals uncertainty times
powerlessness.

00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:19.650
And it's not a plus it's a times because they
have a combustible effect.

00:30:19.650 --> 00:30:23.400
And the truth is when you can take one of
them down closer to zero it actually does

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:27.390
help with the other and it helps to reduce
the anxiety.

00:30:27.390 --> 00:30:31.390
So I decided to create a balance sheet, okay,
another thing I don't know much about, accounting.

00:30:31.390 --> 00:30:35.000
I did go to Stanford Business School but I
hated accounting, didn't like math and I took

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:38.540
one psychology class, what the hell am I doin'
up here?

00:30:38.540 --> 00:30:41.400
[chuckles] But you'll see this anxiety balance
sheet.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:46.470
If you are struggling with something in your
life, in something that's making you a little

00:30:46.470 --> 00:30:50.410
anxious, try this exercise: create four columns.

00:30:50.410 --> 00:30:53.080
The first column is what do I know;

00:30:53.080 --> 00:30:54.230
[pause]

00:30:54.230 --> 00:30:58.910
second column is what don't I know about this
thing that's making me anxious;

00:30:58.910 --> 00:30:59.990
[pause]

00:30:59.990 --> 00:31:03.060
the third column is what can I influence;

